on":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Salvatore, Rocco, Domenic, Mario, Antonio, Santo, Orlando, Americo, Carmine, Gennaro, Luigi, Pasquale, Saverio, Alberico.  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Alicia, Ricardo, Jorge, Juan, Raul, Angel, Atilio.","Italian, Spanish, and Portuguese: nickname for someone of large stature, in either a literal or figurative sense, from <i>grande</i> ‘tall, large’.","German: habitational name from Grande in Holstein or Grand in Bavaria."],"variants":[{"name":"Grant","meanings":["Irish, English, and especially Scottish (of Norman origin): nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>graund</i>, <i>graunt</i> ‘tall, large’ (Old French <i>grand</i>, <i>grant</i>, from Latin <i>grandis</i>), given either to a person of remarkable size, or else in a relative way to distinguish two bearers of the same personal name, often representatives of different generations within the same family.","English: from the rare Middle English (and Old English) personal name <i>Grante</i> or <i>Grente</i>.","Irish: in Ireland this is usually the Norman Scottish name (see 1 above), but it was also adopted for Irish <b>Mag Raighne</b>, see   Graney  ."]},{"name":"Grandi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Elio, Dante, Dino, Geno, Pietro.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of   Grande  ."]},{"name":"De Grandis","meanings":["Italian (rarely <b>Degrandis</b>): patronymic from   Grande  . It is formed with the Latin ablative plural suffix <i>-is</i> imparting the broader sense ‘belonging to, of’, in this case ‘member of the Grandi family’ (compare   Grandi  )."]},{"name":"Del Grande","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Dino, Angelo, Domenic, Marco, Oreste, Reno.","Italian: literally ‘of or belonging to the big one or the great one’ (see   Grande  ), hence a name denoting the son, apprentice, associate, or servant of such a man."]},{"name":"Grannemann","meanings":["German: perhaps a variant of <b>Grandemann</b>, itself a variant of   Grande  ."]},{"name":"Grandinetti","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Aldo, Antonio, Carmin, Domenic, Guido, Martino.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of <b>Grandinetto</b>, a diminutive of   Grande  ."]},{"name":"De Grande","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Romain.","Italian: patronymic from the nickname   Grande   ‘tall, large’.","Flemish (also <b>Degrande</b>): from French and Walloon   Legrand   ‘the tall, the large’. Compare   De Groote  ."]}]},{"name":"Visconti","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Pasquale, Rocco, Umberto, Amerigo, Angelo, Carlo, Domenic, Ennio, Gaetano, Gerlando, Gino.  French Laurent, Camille, Girard.","Italian: from <i>visconte</i>, a title of rank (medieval Latin <i>vicecomes</i> ‘deputy of a count’). Unusually (since most noble families took their surnames from their estates), the surname was sometimes of literal application, but without doubt it is also in part a nickname for someone who gave himself airs and graces, and in part a metonymic occupational name for someone in the employ of a viscount. This surname is also found in southern France."],"variants":[{"name":"Viscomi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Emilio, Salvatore, Antonio, Beniamino, Filomena, Mario, Rodolfo, Santo.","Italian: Sicilian and Calabrian form of   Visconti  , from medieval Latin <i>viscomes</i> ‘deputy’, Greek <i>biskōmēs</i>."]}]},{"name":"Ottone","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Fiore, Sal, Angelo, Antonio, Caesar, Gaetano, Tullio.","Italian:","from a derivative of   Botto  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bottoni","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Rocco, Angelo, Gino, Amato, Domenico, Ettore, Giuseppe, Guido, Marco, Marino, Massimo, Tonino.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of   Bottone  ."]},{"name":"Botto","meanings":["Originally a short form of any of the various Germanic compound personal names containing the element <i>od</i>, <i>ot</i> ‘prosperity, wealth’ (  compare the corresponding Old English <i>ēad</i> in names such as  Edward   and   Edwin  ).  St Otto of Bamberg  (  d. 1139 ) was a missionary to the Pomeranians.  Otto the Great  (  912–73 ) is generally regarded as the founder of the Holy Roman Empire, and the name has been borne by several members of German and Austrian royal houses. It was recorded occasionally among immigrants to England from the Low Countries in the 14th century, but failed to establish itself. Since the 19th century it has again been used occasionally in the English-speaking world, mostly among immigrants from Germanic countries."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ottone Grande Visconti II was born in 1143, in Milan, Lombardy, Italy, his father, Guidone Visconti Feudatario di Massino, Albezzate e Besnate, was 63 and his mother, Garizia of Italy, was 63. He married Aldegunda di Saluzzo in 1141, in Milano, Milan, Lombardy, Italy. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. In 1162, at the age of 19, his occupation is listed as consultore di giustizia in Milan, Lombardy, Italy. He died after 1170, in Milano, Milan, Lombardy, Italy."},"et":{"1143–after 1170":"1143–pärast 1170","1100–1189":"1100–1189","1110–Male":"1110–Surnud","1143–1170":"1143–1170","1124–1153":"1124–1153","1159–Female":"1159–Surnud","–1213":"–1213","1080–1142":"1080–1142","1080–0967":"1080–0967","1080":"1080","after 1170":"pärast 1170","1143":"1143","1110":"1110","1153":"1153","ABT 1159":"umbes 1159","1142":"1142","1162":"1162","1170":"1170","1159":"1159","1213":"1213","1124":"1124","1189":"1189","1100":"1100","0967":"0967","Milano, Lombardia, Italia":"Milano, Lombardia, Itaalia","Milano, Milan, Lombardy, Italy":"Milano, Mil